# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infiniband
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:infiniband/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FCoE transports Fibre Channel directly over Ethernet while being independent of the Ethernet forwarding scheme.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The FCoE protocol specification replaces the FC0 and FC1 layers of the Fibre Channel stack with Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] By retaining the native Fibre Channel constructs, FCoE was meant to integrate with existing Fibre Channel networks and management software.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Traditionally, data centers used both Ethernet for TCP/IP networks and Fibre Channel for SANs, each having different and mostly incompatible interfaces/connections and interconnects/wiring and thus requires separate cabling/wiring and interconnects such as switching hardware for each.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] With the advent of FCoE, SANs that would have traditionally used Fibre Channel is consolidated with Ethernet and becomes another network protocol running on the Ethernet fabric, alongside traditional traffic such as IP.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FCoE operates on top of the data link layer in the OSI model which contrasts with most other well-known protocols that may use Ethernet, such as (for a storage-related example) iSCSI, which runs on top of TCP over IP.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] As a consequence, FCoE is not routable at the IP layer and will not work across routed IP networks such as the Internet.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Since classical Ethernet had no priority-based flow control, unlike Fibre Channel, FCoE required enhancements to the Ethernet standard to support a priority-based flow control mechanism (to reduce frame loss from congestion).
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The IEEE standards body added priorities in the data center bridging (dcb) Task Group.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Computers can connect to FCoE with converged network adapters (CNAs), which contain both Fibre Channel host bus adapter (HBA) and Ethernet network interface controller (NIC) functionality on the same physical card.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] CNAs have one or more physical Ethernet ports.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FCoE encapsulation can be done in software with a conventional Ethernet network interface card, however FCoE CNAs offload (from the CPU) the low level frame processing and SCSI protocol functions traditionally performed by Fibre Channel host bus adapters.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The main application of FCoE is in data center storage area networks (SANs).
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FCoE has particular application in data centers due to the cabling reduction it makes possible, as well as in server virtualization applications, which often require many physical I/O connections per server.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] With FCoE, network (IP) and storage (SAN) data traffic can be consolidated using a single network.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FCoE is encapsulated over Ethernet with the use of a dedicated Ethertype, 0x8906.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] A single 4-bit field (version) satisfies the IEEE sub-type requirements.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The 802.1Q tag is optional but may be necessary in a given implementation.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The SOF (start of frame) and EOF (end of frame) are encoded as specified in RFC 3643.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Reserved bits are present to guarantee that the FCoE frame meets the minimum length requirement of Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Inside the encapsulated Fibre Channel frame, the frame header is retained so as to allow connecting to a storage network by passing on the Fibre Channel frame directly after de-encapsulation.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] The FIP (FCoE Initialization Protocol) is an integral part of FCoE.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Its main goal is to discover and initialize FCoE capable entities connected to an Ethernet cloud.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] FIP uses a dedicated Ethertype of 0x8914.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In October 2003, Azul Technology developed early version and applied for a patent.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In April 2007, the FCoE standardization activity started.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In October 2007, the first public end-to-end FCoE demo occurred at Storage Network World including adapters from QLogic, switches from Nuova Systems, and storage from NetApp (none of the companies involved made any product announcements at the time).
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In April 2008, an early implementor was Nuova Systems, a subsidiary of Cisco Systems, which announced a switch.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Brocade Communications Systems also announced support in 2008.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] After the Great Recession, any new technology had a hard time getting established.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In June 2009, the FCoE technology that had been defined as part of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS) T11 FC-BB-5 standard was forwarded to ANSI for publication.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] In May 2010, the FC-BB-5 standard was published as ANSI/INCITS 462-2010.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel-over-ethernet] Some additional work was done in the INCITS.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel networks form a switched fabric because the switches in a network operate in unison as one big switch.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel typically runs on optical fiber cables within and between data centers, but can also run on copper cabling.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Supported data rates include 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, and 128 gigabit per second resulting from improvements in successive technology generations.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The industry now notates this as Gigabit Fibre Channel (GFC).
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] There are various upper-level protocols for Fibre Channel, including two for block storage.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel Protocol (FCP) is a protocol that transports SCSI commands over Fibre Channel networks.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] FICON is a protocol that transports ESCON commands, used by IBM mainframe computers, over Fibre Channel.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel can be used to transport data from storage systems that use solid-state flash memory storage medium by transporting NVMe protocol commands.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] When the technology was originally devised, it ran over optical fiber cables only and, as such, was called "Fiber Channel".
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Later, the ability to run over copper cabling was added to the specification.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] In order to avoid confusion and to create a unique name, the industry decided to change the spelling and use the British English *fibre* for the name of the standard.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel is standardized in the T11 Technical Committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS), an American National Standards Institute (ANSI)-accredited standards committee.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel started in 1988, with ANSI standard approval in 1994, to merge the benefits of multiple physical layer implementations, including SCSI, HIPPI and ESCON.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel was designed as a serial interface to overcome limitations of the SCSI and HIPPI physical-layer parallel-signal copper wire interfaces.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] This challenge becomes evermore difficult in a mass-manufactured technology as data signal frequencies increase, with part of the technical compensation being ever reducing the supported connecting copper-parallel cable length.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] FC was developed with leading-edge multi-mode optical fiber technologies that overcame the speed limitations of the ESCON protocol.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] By appealing to the large base of SCSI disk drives and leveraging mainframe technologies, Fibre Channel developed economies of scale for advanced technologies and deployments became economical and widespread.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Commercial products were released while the standard was still in draft.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] By the time the standard was ratified, lower speed versions were already growing out of use.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel was the first serial storage transport to achieve gigabit speeds where it saw wide adoption, and its success grew with each successive speed.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel has doubled in speed every few years since 1996.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] In addition to a modern physical layer, Fibre Channel also added support for any number of "upper layer" protocols, including ATM, IP (IPFC) and FICON, with SCSI (FCP) being the predominant usage.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel has seen active development since its inception, with numerous speed improvements on a variety of underlying transport media.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] FC used throughout all applications for Fibre Channel infrastructure and devices, including edge and ISL interconnects.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Inter-Switch Links, ISLs, are usually multi-lane interconnects used for non-edge, core connections, and other high-speed applications demanding maximum bandwidth.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] ISLs utilize high bit-rates to accommodate the funneling of edge connections.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Some ISL solutions are vendor-proprietary.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Two major characteristics of Fibre Channel networks are in-order delivery and lossless delivery of raw block data.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Lossless delivery of raw data block is achieved based on a credit mechanism.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] There are three major Fibre Channel topologies, describing how a number of ports are connected together.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] A *port* in Fibre Channel terminology is any entity that actively communicates over the network, not necessarily a hardware port.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] This port is usually implemented in a device such as disk storage, a Host Bus Adapter (HBA) network connection on a server or a Fibre Channel switch.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel products are available at 1, 2, 4, 8, 10, 16, 32, 64 and 128 Gbit/s; these protocol flavors are called accordingly 1GFC, 2GFC, 4GFC, 8GFC, 10GFC, 16GFC, 32GFC, 64GFC or 128GFC.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The 32GFC standard was approved by the INCITS T11 committee in 2013, and those products became available in 2016.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The 1GFC, 2GFC, 4GFC, 8GFC designs all use 8b/10b encoding, while the 10GFC and 16GFC standard uses 64b/66b encoding.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Unlike the 10GFC standards, 16GFC provides backward compatibility with 4GFC and 8GFC since it provides exactly twice the throughput of 8GFC or four times that of 4GFC.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel ports come in a variety of logical configurations.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The Fibre Channel physical layer is based on serial connections that use fiber optics to copper between corresponding pluggable modules.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The modules may have a single lane, dual lanes or quad lanes that correspond to the SFP, SFP-DD and QSFP form factors.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel does not use 8- or 16-lane modules (like CFP8, QSFP-DD, or COBO used in 400GbE) and there are no plans to use these expensive and complex modules.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) module and its enhanced version SFP+, SFP28 and SFP56 are common form factors for Fibre Channel ports.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] SFP modules support a variety of distances via multi-mode and single-mode optical fiber as shown in the table below.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] SFP modules use duplex fiber cabling with LC connectors.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] SFP-DD modules are used for high-density applications that need to double the throughput of an SFP Port.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] SFP-DD is defined by the SFP-DD MSA and enables breakout to two SFP ports.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Two rows of electrical contacts enable doubling the throughput of SFP modules in a similar fashion as QSFP-DD.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The Quad Small Form-factor Pluggable (QSFP) module began being used for switch inter-connectivity and was later adopted for use in 4-lane implementations of Gen-6 Fibre Channel supporting 128GFC.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] QSFP uses either LC connectors for 128GFC-CWDM4 or MPO connectors for 128GFC-SW4 or 128GFC-PSM4.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] MPO cabling uses 8- or 12-fiber cabling infrastructure that connects to another 128GFC port or may be broken out into four duplex LC connections to 32GFC SFP+ ports.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel switches use either SFP or QSFP modules.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Modern Fibre Channel devices support SFP+ transceivers, mainly with LC (Lucent Connector) fiber connector.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Older 1GFC devices used GBIC transceivers, mainly with SC (Subscriber Connector) fiber connectors.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The goal of Fibre Channel is to create a storage area network (SAN) to connect servers to storage.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] The SAN is a dedicated network that enables multiple servers to access data from one or more storage devices.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Enterprise storage uses the SAN to backup to secondary storage devices, including disk arrays, tape libraries, and other backup, while the storage is still accessible to the server.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Servers may access storage from multiple storage devices over the network as well.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] SANs are often designed with dual fabrics to increase fault tolerance.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Two completely separate fabrics are operational and if the primary fabric fails, then the second fabric becomes the primary.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel switches can be divided into two classes.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] A fabric consisting entirely of one vendor's products is considered to be *homogeneous*.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] This is often referred to as operating in its "native mode" and allows the vendor to add proprietary features that may not be compliant with the Fibre Channel standard.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] If multiple switch vendors are used within the same fabric, it is *heterogeneous*, the switches may only achieve adjacency if all switches are placed into their interoperability modes.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] This is called the *open fabric* mode, as each vendor's switch may have to disable its proprietary features to comply with the Fibre Channel standard.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Some switch manufacturers offer a variety of interoperability modes above and beyond the "native" and "open fabric" states.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] These "native interoperability" modes allow switches to operate in the native mode of another vendor and still maintain some of the proprietary behaviors of both.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] However, running in native interoperability mode may still disable some proprietary features and can produce fabrics of questionable stability.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Fibre Channel HBAs, as well as CNAs, are available for all major open systems, computer architectures, and buses, including PCI and SBus.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] HBAs connect servers to the Fibre Channel network and are part of a class of devices known as translation devices.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Each HBA has a unique World Wide Name (WWN), which is similar to an Ethernet MAC address in that it uses an Organizationally Unique Identifier (OUI) assigned by the IEEE.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] There are two types of WWNs on an HBA; a World Wide Node Name (WWNN), which can be shared by some or all ports of a device, and a World Wide Port Name (WWPN), which is necessarily unique to each port.
[src:infiniband/fibre-channel] Adapters or routers can connect Fibre Channel networks to IP or Ethernet networks.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Mellanox (acquired by Nvidia) manufactures InfiniBand host bus adapters and network switches, which are used by large computer system and database vendors in their product lines.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] As a computer cluster interconnect, IB competes with Ethernet, Fibre Channel, and Intel Omni-Path.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The technology is promoted by the **InfiniBand Trade Association**.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] InfiniBand originated in 1999 from the merger of two competing designs: Future I/O and Next Generation I/O (NGIO).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] NGIO was led by Intel, with a specification released in 1998, and joined by Sun Microsystems and Dell.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Future I/O was backed by Compaq, IBM, and Hewlett-Packard.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] This led to the formation of the InfiniBand Trade Association (IBTA), which included both sets of hardware vendors as well as software vendors such as Microsoft.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] At the time it was thought some of the more powerful computers were approaching the interconnect bottleneck of the PCI bus, in spite of upgrades like PCI-X.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Version 1.0 of the InfiniBand Architecture Specification was released in 2000.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Initially the IBTA vision for IB was simultaneously a replacement for PCI in I/O, Ethernet in the machine room, cluster interconnect and Fibre Channel.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] IBTA also envisaged decomposing server hardware on an IB fabric.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Mellanox had been founded in 1999 to develop NGIO technology, but by 2001 shipped an InfiniBand product line called InfiniBridge at 10 Gbit/second speeds.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Following the burst of the dot-com bubble there was hesitation in the industry to invest in such a far-reaching technology jump.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] By 2002, Intel announced that instead of shipping IB integrated circuits ("chips"), it would focus on developing PCI Express, and Microsoft discontinued IB development in favor of extending Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Sun Microsystems and Hitachi continued to support IB.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In 2003, the System X supercomputer built at Virginia Tech used InfiniBand in what was estimated to be the third largest computer in the world at the time.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The OpenIB Alliance (later renamed OpenFabrics Alliance) was founded in 2004 to develop an open set of software for the Linux kernel.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] By February, 2005, the support was accepted into the 2.6.11 Linux kernel.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In November 2005 storage devices finally were released using InfiniBand from vendors such as Engenio.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Cisco, desiring to keep technology superior to Ethernet off the market, adopted a "buy to kill" strategy.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Cisco successfully killed InfiniBand switching companies such as Topspin via acquisition.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Of the top 500 supercomputers in 2009, Gigabit Ethernet was the internal interconnect technology in 259 installations, compared with 181 using InfiniBand.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In 2010, market leaders Mellanox and Voltaire merged, leaving just one other IB vendor, QLogic, primarily a Fibre Channel vendor.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] At the 2011 International Supercomputing Conference, links running at about 56 gigabits per second (known as FDR, see below), were announced and demonstrated by connecting booths in the trade show.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In 2012, Intel acquired QLogic's InfiniBand technology, leaving only one independent supplier.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] By 2014, InfiniBand was the most popular internal connection technology for supercomputers, although within two years, 10 Gigabit Ethernet started displacing it.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In 2016, it was reported that Oracle Corporation (an investor in Mellanox) might engineer its own InfiniBand hardware.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In 2019 Nvidia acquired Mellanox, the last independent supplier of InfiniBand products.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Specifications are published by the InfiniBand trade association.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Original names for speeds were single-data rate (SDR), double-data rate (DDR) and quad-data rate (QDR) as given below.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Subsequently, other three-letter initialisms were added for even higher data rates.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Links can be aggregated: most systems use a 4 link/lane connector (QSFP).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] HDR often makes use of 2x links (aka HDR100, 100 Gb link using 2 lanes of HDR, while still using a QSFP connector).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] NDR introduced OSFP connectors which host one or two links at 2x (NDR200) or 4x (NDR400).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] They are not logically configured as a single 8x link, even when connecting switches together with an OSFP cable.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] InfiniBand provides remote direct memory access (RDMA) capabilities for low CPU overhead.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] InfiniBand uses a switched fabric topology, as opposed to early shared medium Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] All transmissions begin or end at a channel adapter.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Each processor contains a host channel adapter (HCA) and each peripheral has a target channel adapter (TCA).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] These adapters can also exchange information for security or quality of service (QoS).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] InfiniBand transmits data in packets of up to 4 KB that are taken together to form a message.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] In addition to a board form factor connection, it can use both active and passive copper (up to 10 meters) and optical fiber cable (up to 10 km).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The InfiniBand Association also specified the CXP connector system for speeds up to 120 Gbit/s over copper, active optical cables, and optical transceivers using parallel multi-mode fiber cables with 24-fiber MPO connectors.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Mellanox operating system support is available for Solaris, FreeBSD, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES), Windows, HP-UX, VMware ESX, and AIX.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] InfiniBand has no specific standard application programming interface (API).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The standard only lists a set of verbs such as `ibv_open_device` or `ibv_post_send`, which are abstract representations of functions or methods that must exist.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The syntax of these functions is left to the vendors.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Sometimes for reference this is called the *verbs* API.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The de facto standard software is developed by OpenFabrics Alliance and called the Open Fabrics Enterprise Distribution (OFED).
[src:infiniband/infiniband] It is released under two licenses GPL2 or BSD license for Linux and FreeBSD, and as Mellanox OFED for Windows (product names: WinOF / WinOF-2; attributed as host controller driver for matching specific ConnectX 3 to 5 devices) under a choice of BSD license for Windows.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] It has been adopted by most of the InfiniBand vendors, for Linux, FreeBSD, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] IBM refers to a software library called `libibverbs`, for its AIX operating system, as well as "AIX InfiniBand verbs".
[src:infiniband/infiniband] The Linux kernel support was integrated in 2005 into the kernel version 2.6.11.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Ethernet over InfiniBand, abbreviated to EoIB, is an Ethernet implementation over the InfiniBand protocol and connector technology.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] EoIB enables multiple Ethernet bandwidths varying on the InfiniBand (IB) version.
[src:infiniband/infiniband] Ethernet's implementation of the Internet Protocol Suite, usually referred to as TCP/IP, is different in some details compared to the direct InfiniBand protocol in IP over IB (IPoIB).
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:infiniband/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:infiniband/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] In computing, **remote direct memory access** (**RDMA**) is direct memory access from the memory of one computer into that of another without involving either computer's operating system.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] This permits high-throughput, low-latency memory access over a network, which is especially useful in massively parallel computer clusters.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] RDMA supports zero-copy networking by enabling the network adapter to transfer data from the wire directly to application memory or from application memory directly to the wire, eliminating the need to copy data between application memory and the data buffers in the operating system.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Such transfers require no work to be done by CPUs, caches, or context switches, and transfers continue in parallel with other system operations.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] This reduces latency in message transfer.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] However, this strategy presents several problems related to the fact that the target node is not notified of the completion of the request (single-sided communications).
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] As of 2018 RDMA had achieved broader acceptance as a result of implementation enhancements that enable good performance over ordinary networking infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] For example RDMA over Converged Ethernet (RoCE) now is able to run over either lossy or lossless infrastructure.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] In addition iWARP enables an Ethernet RDMA implementation at the physical layer using TCP/IP as the transport, combining the performance and latency advantages of RDMA with a low-cost, standards-based solution.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] The RDMA Consortium and the DAT Collaborative have played key roles in the development of RDMA protocols and APIs for consideration by standards groups such as the Internet Engineering Task Force and the Interconnect Software Consortium.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Hardware vendors have started working on higher-capacity RDMA-based network adapters, with rates of 100 Gbit/s reported.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Software vendors, such as IBM, Red Hat and Oracle Corporation, support these APIs in their latest products, and since 2013, engineers have been developing network adapters that implement RDMA over Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Both Red Hat Enterprise Linux and Red Hat Enterprise MRG have support for RDMA.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Microsoft supports RDMA in Windows Server 2012 via SMB Direct.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] VMware ESXi also supports RDMA as of 2015.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Common RDMA implementations include the Virtual Interface Architecture, RDMA over Converged Ethernet (RoCE), InfiniBand, Omni-Path, iWARP and Ultra Ethernet.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Applications access control structures using well-defined APIs originally designed for the InfiniBand Protocol (although the APIs can be used for any of the underlying RDMA implementations).
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] Using send and completion queues, applications perform RDMA operations by submitting work queue entries (WQEs) into the submission queue (SQ) and getting notified of responses from the completion queue (CQ).
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] RDMA can transport data reliably or unreliably over the Reliably Connected (RC) and Unreliable Datagram (UD) transport protocols, respectively.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] The former has the benefit of preserving requests (no requests are lost), while the latter requires fewer queue pairs when handling multiple connections.
[src:infiniband/remote-direct-memory-access] This is due to the fact that UD is connection-less, allowing a single host to communicate with any other using a single queue.
